ANTH-UA 9038 Indigenous Australian Art: An analytical survey, Anthropology | New York University                                     NEW YORK UNIVERSITY       ARTS AND SCIENCE       COLLEGE OF ARTS AND SCIENCE       GRADUATE SCHOOL OF ARTS AND SCIENCE                                                                         Back to Home         ANTH-UA 9038 Indigenous Australian Art: An analytical survey   This course is a survey of the principal themes and issues in the   development of Indigenous art in Australia. It focuses on some of the   regional and historical variations of Aboriginal art in the context of   the history of a settler nation, while considering the issues of its   circulation and evaluation within contemporary discourses of value.   Topics include the cosmological dimensions of the art, its political   implications, its relationship to cultural identity, and its aesthetic   frameworks. Students will visit some of the major national collections   of Indigenous Australian art as well as exhibitions of contemporary   works. There will also be guest presentations from Indigenous artists   and Indigenous art curators.                         Contact Us | © New York University , Arts and Science

ANTH-UA 9038 Indigenous Australian Art: An analytical survey, Anthropology | New York University                                     NEW YORK UNIVERSITY       ARTS AND SCIENCE       COLLEGE OF ARTS AND SCIENCE       GRADUATE SCHOOL OF ARTS AND SCIENCE                                                                         Back to Home         ANTH-UA 9038 Indigenous Australian Art: An analytical survey   This course is a survey of the principal themes and issues in the   development of Indigenous art in Australia. It focuses on some of the   regional and historical variations of Aboriginal art in the context of   the history of a settler nation, while considering the issues of its   circulation and evaluation within contemporary discourses of value.   Topics include the cosmological dimensions of the art, its political   implications, its relationship to cultural identity, and its aesthetic   frameworks. Students will visit some of the major national collections   of Indigenous Australian art as well as exhibitions of contemporary   works. There will also be guest presentations from Indigenous artists   and Indigenous art curators.                         Contact Us | © New York University , Arts and Science
